#X obj 581 107 bp~ 3000 10, f 21;
#X text 65 39 The vanilla [bp~] (from "bandpass") object receives control data for frequency and "Q". It's quite simple and CPU efficient \, but not a perfectly symmetric bandpass filter \, atenuatting more the frequencies above the resonant frequency., f 64;
#X text 665 60 Central/Resonant Frequency;
#X obj 754 14 declare -path else;
#X obj 581 143 out~;
#X text 65 103 This filter actually looks more like a resonant lowpass with a gain adjustment so the central frequency is at 0 dB. This will be clearer when we see resonant lowpass filters. And about this \, note also how a "Q" of 1 makes it quite similar to the [lop~] object. Like other vanilla filters already shown here \, the response changes for very high frequencies., f 64;
